In life, the popliteal fossa is enclosed superficially by the deep fascia of the leg, which is continuous superiorly with the fascia lata and inferiorly with the crural fascia.
The superficial fascia in this region contains the small saphenous vein and cutaneous nerves. The small saphenous vein pierces the deep fascia overlying the popliteal fossa and empties into the popliteal vein.
